revision.text:
{{ページ番号|date=2015th year 10月}} '''Tenmei no Taika''' (天明の大火) refers to a [[fire]] that occurred in [[Kyoto]] on {{nihongo|January 30, Tenmei 8|天明8th year 1月30日|1788th year }} (March 7, 1788, in the [[Gregorian calendar]]). Known as '''Donguri-yake''' (団栗焼け) after the name of the location where it originated, it is also called the '''Saru-doshi no Taika''' (申年の大火, "Great Fire of the Year of the Monkey") based on the Chinese zodiac. Simply calling it the '''Kyoto Great Fire''' (京都大火) or '''Miyako-yake''' (都焼け, "Burning of the Capital") usually refers to this specific event.
It was the largest fire in Kyoto's history, destroying the [[Kyoto Imperial Palace|Imperial Palace]], [[Nijō Castle]], and the [[Kyoto Shoshidai]] along with over 80% of the city. The damage surpassed the devastation caused by the [[Ōnin War]] and left a lasting impact on Kyoto's economy. Together with the [[Hōei no Taika]] and the [[Dondon-yake]] during the [[Genji era]], these are sometimes referred to as Kyoto's "Three Great Fires."<ref>''{{ill|Kokushi Daijiten|ja|国史大辞典|12=draft|12=draft}}'', Volume 9 (Yoshikawa Kōbunkan, 1988), entry "Tenmei no Kyoto Taika" (author: Katsuhisa Moriya).</ref>
== Overview == The fire broke out early in the morning of January 30 (March 7), originating from a [[row house]] in {{nihongo|Miyagawa Town Donguri Zushi|宮川町団栗辻子|Miyagawa-chō Dōnguri Zushi}}, east of the {{ill|Kamo River (Yodo River system)|ja|鴨川 (淀川水系)|12=draft|12=draft}} in present-day {{ill|Higashiyama Ward, Kyoto|ja|京都市東山区|12=draft|12=draft}}. It was reportedly an arson attack on a vacant house. Strong winds quickly spread the fire south to {{ill|Gojō Street|ja|五条通|12=draft|12=draft}} and then across the river to {{ill|Teramachi Street|ja|寺町通|12=draft|12=draft}}, engulfing the city center. By the evening, the flames reached Nijō Castle's inner keep and continued north to the Imperial Palace. The fire was finally extinguished early on February 2 (March 9), two days after it began.
The fire spread as far east as {{ill|Kawaramachi Street|ja|河原町通|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kiyamachi Street|ja|木屋町|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Yamato Ōji Street|ja|大和大路|12=draft|12=draft}}; north to {{ill|Kamigoryō Shrine|ja|上御霊神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kuramaguchi Street|ja|鞍馬口通|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Imamiya Shrine Temporary Worship Site|ja|今宮御旅所|12=draft|12=draft}}; west to {{ill|Chiekōin Street|ja|智恵光院通|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōmiya Street|ja|大宮通|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Senbon Street|ja|千本通|12=draft|12=draft}}; and south to {{ill|Higashi Honganji|ja|東本願寺|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nishi Honganji|ja|西本願寺|12=draft|12=draft}}, and Rokujō Street. The destruction included not only the Imperial Palace and Nijō Castle but also the {{ill|Sentō Imperial Palace|ja|仙洞御所|12=draft|12=draft}}, the Kyoto Shoshidai residence, the {{ill|Kyoto Machibugyō|ja|京都町奉行|12=draft|12=draft}} offices, and the mansions of the {{ill|Five regent houses|ja|摂関家|Five regent houses=Five regent houses|lt=Sesshō and Kampaku families|12=draft|12=draft}}. Official records from the Kyoto [[Chōdai]] (町代) estimate the damage as follows: 1,424 out of 1,967 city wards burned, 36,797 houses destroyed, 65,340 households affected, 201 temples, 37 shrines lost, and 150 deaths. However, some suspect the death toll was understated, with estimates suggesting as many as 1,800 casualties.
[[Emperor Kōkaku]] lived at the {{ill|Shōgoin Temple|ja|聖護院|12=draft|12=draft}} as a temporary palace for three years until the Imperial Palace was rebuilt. {{nihongo|Dowager Empress Go-Sakuramachi|後桜町上皇}} moved to the {{ill|Shōren-in|ja|青蓮院|12=draft|12=draft}}, while her mother, Seiki Mon’in, took up residence at {{ill|Chion-in|ja|知恩院|12=draft|12=draft}}. To facilitate travel between Chion-in and Shōren-in, a corridor was built by the [[Tokugawa shogunate|shogunate]].
Shocked by the disaster, the [[Tokugawa shogunate]] dispatched senior {{ill|Rōjū|ja|老中|12=draft|12=draft}} {{nihongo|Matsudaira Sadanobu|松平定信}} to Kyoto to discuss recovery measures with the Imperial Court. Shortly afterward, {{nihongo|The Illustrated Commentary on the Imperial Palace|大内裏図考證}}, authored by Uramatsu Kozan, was completed. The reconstruction of the Imperial Palace followed its traditional style based on these studies. Despite the shogunate's chronic financial difficulties and public suffering during the {{ill|Tenmei famine|ja|天明の大飢饉|12=draft|12=draft}}, funding was provided for the project. Matsudaira Sadanobu, who opposed extravagant rebuilding, later ordered Kyoto officials to reject new demands from the court, leading to tensions and eventually contributing to disputes such as the {{ill|Respectful Title Incident|ja|尊号一件|12=draft|12=draft}}.
Ten years after the fire, on {{nihongo|July 1, Kansei 10|寛政10th year 7月1日|1798}}, the {{ill|Hōkō-ji Daibutsu|ja|方広寺大仏|12=draft|12=draft}} (Great Buddha of Kyoto) and its hall were destroyed by lightning-induced fire. Although this fire threatened to cause another city-wide disaster like the Tenmei fire, it miraculously did not spread beyond the vicinity.<ref>{{Cite book|和書|author=村山修一|title=京都大仏御殿盛衰記|publisher=法藏館|year=2003}}</ref>
